---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { navItems, footerLinks, pillarLinks, topic } from '../data/site';

const cards = [
  {
    title: 'Regional Overview',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/`,
    summary: 'Start with the shared vocabulary, ingredient logic, and everyday uses that make sambal central to the Southeast Asian table.',
  },
  {
    title: 'History & Evolution',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/history/`,
    summary: 'Trace how older pepper condiments, colonial trade, and regional migration shaped modern sambal forms.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Kitchen Technique',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/technical-deep-dive/`,
    summary: 'Learn how grinding texture, aromatics, oil, salt, and acid affect flavor, stability, and finish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Sambal Vocabulary',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/ontology/`,
    summary: 'Use the glossary and taxonomy to understand fresh, cooked, fermented, and dish-specific sambal families.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Current Trends',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/trends/`,
    summary: 'See how chefs, diaspora cooks, and pantry brands are adapting sambal for contemporary kitchens.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Tools & Resources',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/tools/`,
    summary: 'Use practical calculators and substitution guides designed for real home-cooking decisions.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Challenges & Solutions',
    href: `/${topic.slug}/challenges/`,
    summary: 'Fix bitterness, watery texture, imbalanced heat, and storage problems with grounded troubleshooting advice.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Cafe Sambal | Southeast Asian Sambal Traditions and Techniques"
  description="Cafe Sambal explores regional sambal traditions, chili pastes, and practical home-cooking methods across Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore."
  navItems={navItems}
  footerLinks={footerLinks}
>
  <section class="hero page-shell">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Southeast Asian condiment research for everyday cooks</p>
      <h1>Cafe Sambal maps the traditions, techniques, and kitchen logic behind regional sambal.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        This site focuses on how sambal actually functions in home cooking: as a condiment, a frying base,
        a flavor concentrator, and a marker of place. Rather than treating sambal as a single recipe, Cafe Sambal
        compares ingredient choices and cooking patterns across Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore.
      </p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/`} class="primary">Explore the overview</a>
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/tools/`} class="secondary">Open kitchen tools</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hero-panel">
      <h2>What you’ll find here</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Region-by-region sambal comparisons grounded in real culinary context.</li>
        <li>Kitchen technique explanations for texture, heat, balance, and shelf life.</li>
        <li>Interactive tools for scaling, substitutions, and heat-balancing decisions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-shell intro-grid">
    <article>
      <h2>Why focus on sambal as a system rather than a single recipe?</h2>
      <p>
        Sambal is often introduced through one iconic formula, but cooks quickly discover that the category is much broader.
        Some sambals are raw and bright, built around fresh chilies, herbs, and citrus. Others are cooked down in oil for a rounder,
        sweeter finish. Many rely on fermented ingredients, while others emphasize clean heat and immediate freshness. Looking at sambal
        as a system helps explain why a condiment that appears simple can vary so dramatically between island cuisines, household preferences,
        and restaurant contexts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Cafe Sambal is organized around the site’s seven core pillars so readers can move from foundation to application. The
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/`}>overview page</a> introduces the central vocabulary and everyday uses, the
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/history/`}>history page</a> explains how trade and migration shaped chili condiments, and the
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/technical-deep-dive/`}>technical guide</a> breaks down how texture and ingredient function affect results.
        From there, the <a href={`/${topic.slug}/ontology/`}>ontology page</a>,
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/trends/`}>trends report</a>,
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/tools/`}>tools library</a>, and
        <a href={`/${topic.slug}/challenges/`}>troubleshooting hub</a> help readers deepen practice instead of just copying recipes.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>Selected site angle</h2>
      <p>
        The first build for this domain centers on <strong>regional sambal traditions</strong>. That means the site compares the practical
        cooking logic behind sambal from different places, not just ingredient lists. A home cook reading about sambal terasi, sambal belacan,
        sambal hijau, or sambal kecap should come away understanding what problem each one solves at the table and how method affects flavor.
      </p>
      <p>
        This angle creates a stronger knowledge base than a typical blog because it supports history, glossary work, tool development,
        and troubleshooting with a single subject at the center. It also keeps the site differentiated from future food domains in the batch.
        When you're ready to bring cafe-quality drinks into your own kitchen, this <a href="https://completehomebarista.com/guides/complete-beginner/">beginner espresso guide</a> is a natural next step.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="page-shell cards-section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Core reading path</p>
      <h2>Seven pillar pages for understanding regional sambal traditions</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="cards">
      {cards.map((card) => (
        <a class="card" href={card.href}>
          <h3>{card.title}</h3>
          <p>{card.summary}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .hero {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.9fr) minmax(280px, 1fr);
    gap: 2rem;
    align-items: center;
    padding-top: 3rem;
  }
  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    color: #c2410c;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 800;
  }
  h1 {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 4vw, 4.2rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    color: #431407;
  }
  .lead {
    font-size: 1.08rem;
    line-height: 1.9;
    color: #5b3a29;
  }
  .actions {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
  }
  .primary,
  .secondary {
    padding: 0.85rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .primary {
    background: #c2410c;
    color: white;
  }
  .secondary {
    background: #fff7ed;
    color: #7c2d12;
    border: 1px solid rgba(124, 45, 18, 0.15);
  }
  .hero-panel,
  .intro-grid article,
  .card {
    background: rgba(255, 250, 245, 0.8);
    border: 1px solid rgba(124, 45, 18, 0.12);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    box-shadow: 0 18px 45px rgba(124, 45, 18, 0.08);
  }
  .hero-panel {
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }
  .hero-panel h2,
  .intro-grid h2,
  .section-head h2,
  .card h3 {
    color: #7c2d12;
  }
  .hero-panel ul {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
  .intro-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
  .intro-grid article {
    padding: 1.5rem;
  }
  .intro-grid p {
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: #4b3325;
  }
  .cards-section {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .card {
    padding: 1.35rem;
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .card p {
    color: #5b3a29;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  @media (max-width: 960px) {
    .hero,
    .intro-grid,
    .cards {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
